PRNGs leading to density and irrationality pro ofs Independent of number theory and special primes, one could ask what is the statistical behavior of truly random points chosen modulo 1; for example, what are the expected gaps that work against uniform point density? In view of Definition 2.1(4) and Theorem 2.2(11), it behooves us to ponder the expected gap-maximum for random points: If N random (with uniform distribution) points are placed in [0, 1), then the probability that the gap-maximum GN exceeds x is known to be [30] Prob(GN x) = 1/x j =1
